ce:section.ce:para:
The stability and average droplet size of Pickering emulsions are usually affected by factors such as the organic solvent, sonication time, solid particle concentration, water/oil ratio, pH and salt concentration [1]. In this work, a dozen organic solvents including both aromatic compounds and non-aromatic compounds were used as the continuous phase (outer phase) to prepare inverse Pickering emulsions (Fig. 1
                        ). Two common methods (staining and dilution) were usually employed to identify the type of prepared emulsions. First, Sudan III, an oil-soluble biological stain, was added to the prepared Pickering emulsions. Then a drop of the colored emulsion was smeared homogeneously on a glass slide and observed under a microscope. A typical example is shown in Fig. 2
                        e, when the dye was added, the color of the outer phase of the emulsion changed from milky white to orange yellow. The dilution method is based on the fact that an emulsion can be diluted by its outer phase or by another liquid with the similar polarity as the outer phase. As shown by the representative picture (inset in Fig. 2e), none of the emulsions were dispersible in water. Thus the results of the two methods are consistent i.e. at steady state, all the emulsions are inverse types.
